# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: organometallic-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] In organic chemistry, a **cross-coupling reaction** is a reaction where two different fragments are joined.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Cross-couplings are a subset of the more general coupling reactions.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Often cross-coupling reactions require metal catalysts.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] These reactions are used to form carbon–carbon bonds but also carbon-heteroatom bonds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Cross-coupling reaction are a subset of coupling reactions.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Heck, Ei-ichi Negishi, and Akira Suzuki were awarded the 2010 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for developing palladium-catalyzed coupling reactions.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Many mechanisms exist reflecting the myriad types of cross-couplings, including those that do not require metal catalysts.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Often, however, cross-coupling refers to a metal-catalyzed reaction of a nucleophilic partner with an electrophilic partner.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] In such cases, the mechanism generally involves reductive elimination of R-R' from LnMR(R') (L = spectator ligand).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] This intermediate LnMR(R') is formed in a two-step process from a low valence precursor LnM.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] The oxidative addition of an organic halide (RX) to LnM gives LnMR(X).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Subsequently, the second partner undergoes transmetallation with a source of R'−.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] The final step is reductive elimination of the two coupling fragments to regenerate the catalyst and give the organic product.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Unsaturated substrates, such as C(sp)−X and C(sp2)−X bonds, couple more easily, in part because they add readily to the catalyst.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Catalysts are often based on palladium, which is frequently selected due to high functional group tolerance.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Organopalladium compounds are generally stable towards water and air.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Palladium catalysts can be problematic for the pharmaceutical industry, which faces extensive regulation regarding heavy metals.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Many pharmaceutical chemists attempt to use coupling reactions early in production to minimize metal traces in the product.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Heterogeneous catalysts based on Pd are also well-developed.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Alternatives to palladium cross-couplings became prevalent in the 2000s, with interest in non-precious and less toxic metals.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Copper-based catalysts are especially useful for coupling involving heteroatom-C bonds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Iron- and cobalt-catalysis have also been investigated.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] The use of nickel-based catalysis has become more widespread.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] The leaving group X in the organic partner is usually a halide, although triflate, tosylate, pivalate esters, carbamates, and other pseudohalides have been used.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Chloride is an ideal group due to the low cost of organochlorine compounds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Frequently, however, C–Cl bonds are too inert, and bromide or iodide leaving groups are required for acceptable rates.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] The main group metal in the organometallic partner is usually an electropositive element such as tin, zinc, silicon, or boron.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Many cross-couplings entail forming carbon–carbon bonds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] The restrictions on carbon atom geometry mainly inhibit β-hydride elimination when complexed to the catalyst.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Many cross-couplings entail forming carbon–heteroatom bonds (heteroatom = S, N, O).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Palladium-catalyzes the cross-coupling of aryl halides with fluorinated arene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] The process is unusual in that it involves C–H functionalisation at an electron deficient arene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] A new class of cross-couplings was discovered in 2015 by the research teams of Neil Garg and Ken Houk involving amides as coupling partners.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Nickel catalysis breaks the typical strong C-N bonds of amides through oxidative addition.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Using nickel or palladium, transformations of amides can be achieved, including esterification, transamidation, hydrolysis, Suzuki-Miyaura couplings, and asymmetric Heck reactions.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Cross-coupling reactions are important for the production of pharmaceuticals, examples being montelukast, eletriptan, naproxen, varenicline, and resveratrol. with Suzuki coupling being most widely used.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/cross-coupling-reaction] Some polymers and monomers are also prepared in this way.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The first reported synthesis of ferrocene was in 1951.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Its unusual stability puzzled chemists, and required the development of new theory to explain its formation and bonding.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The discovery of ferrocene and its many structural analogues, known as metallocenes, sparked excitement and led to a rapid growth in the discipline of organometallic chemistry.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Geoffrey Wilkinson and Ernst Otto Fischer, both of whom worked on elucidating the structure of ferrocene, later shared the 1973 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their work on organometallic sandwich compounds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene itself has no large-scale applications, but has found more niche uses in catalysis, as a fuel additive, as an internal standard in electrochemical research, and as a tool in undergraduate education.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene was discovered by accident twice.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The first known synthesis may have been made in the late 1940s by unknown researchers at Union Carbide, who tried to pass hot cyclopentadiene vapor through an iron pipe.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The vapor reacted with the pipe wall, creating a "yellow sludge" that clogged the pipe.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Years later, a sample of the sludge that had been saved was obtained and analyzed by Eugene O.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Brimm, shortly after reading Kealy and Pauson's article, and was found to consist of ferrocene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The second time was around 1950, when Samuel A.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Tremaine, researchers at British Oxygen, were attempting to synthesize amines from hydrocarbons and nitrogen in a modification of the Haber process.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] When they tried to react cyclopentadiene with nitrogen at 300 °C (572 °F), at atmospheric pressure, they were disappointed to see the hydrocarbon react with some source of iron, yielding ferrocene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] While they too observed its remarkable stability, they put the observation aside and did not publish it until after Pauson reported his findings.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Kealy and Pauson were later provided with a sample by Miller *et al.*, who confirmed that the products were the same compound.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Kealy at Duquesne University attempted to prepare fulvalene ((C5H4)2) by oxidative dimerization of cyclopentadiene (C5H6).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] To that end, they reacted the Grignard compound cyclopentadienyl magnesium bromide in diethyl ether with iron(III) chloride as an oxidizer.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] However, instead of the expected fulvalene, they obtained a light orange powder of "remarkable stability", with the formula C10H10Fe.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Pauson and Kealy conjectured that the compound had two cyclopentadienyl groups, each with a single covalent bond from the saturated carbon atom to the iron atom.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] However, that structure was inconsistent with then-existing bonding models and did not explain the unexpected stability of the compound, and chemists struggled to find the correct structure.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The structure was deduced and reported independently by three groups in 1952.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Robert Burns Woodward, Geoffrey Wilkinson, et al. observed that the compound was diamagnetic and nonpolar.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] A few months later they described its reactions as being typical of aromatic compounds such as benzene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The name ferrocene was coined by Mark Whiting, a postdoc with Woodward.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ernst Otto Fischer and Wolfgang Pfab also noted ferrocene's diamagneticity and high symmetry.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] They also synthesized nickelocene and cobaltocene and confirmed they had the same structure.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Fischer described the structure as *Doppelkegelstruktur* ("double-cone structure"), although the term "sandwich" came to be preferred by British and American chemists.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Philip Frank Eiland and Raymond Pepinsky confirmed the structure through X-ray crystallography and later by NMR spectroscopy.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The "sandwich" structure of ferrocene was very novel and led to intensive theoretical studies.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Application of molecular orbital theory with the assumption of a Fe2+ centre between two cyclopentadienide anions C5H−5 resulted in the successful Dewar–Chatt–Duncanson model, allowing correct prediction of the geometry of the molecule as well as explaining its remarkable stability.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The discovery of ferrocene was considered so significant that Wilkinson and Fischer shared the 1973 Nobel Prize in Chemistry "for their pioneering work, performed independently, on the chemistry of the organometallic, called sandwich compounds".
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Mössbauer spectroscopy indicates that the iron center in ferrocene should be assigned the +2 oxidation state.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Each cyclopentadienyl (Cp) ring should then be allocated a single negative charge.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Thus ferrocene could be described as iron(II) bis(cyclopentadienide), Fe2+[C5H−5]2.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Each ring has six π-electrons, which makes them aromatic according to Hückel's rule.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] These π-electrons are then shared with the metal via covalent bonding.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Since Fe2+ has six *d*-electrons, the complex attains an 18-electron configuration, which accounts for its stability.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] In modern notation, this sandwich structural model of the ferrocene molecule is denoted as Fe(η5-C5H5)2, where *η* denotes hapticity, the number of atoms through which each ring binds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The carbon–carbon bond distances around each five-membered ring are all 1.440 Å, and all Fe–C bond distances are 2.064 Å.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The Cp rings rotate with a low barrier about the Cp(centroid)–Fe–Cp(centroid) axis, as observed by measurements on substituted derivatives of ferrocene using 1H and 13C nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] For example, methylferrocene (CH3C5H4FeC5H5) exhibits a singlet for the C5H5 ring.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] From room temperature down to 164 K (−164 °F; −109 °C), X-ray crystallography yields the monoclinic space group; the cyclopentadienide rings are a staggered conformation, resulting in a centrosymmetric molecule, with symmetry group D5d.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] However, below 110 K (−262 °F; −163 °C), ferrocene crystallizes in an orthorhombic crystal lattice in which the Cp rings are ordered and eclipsed, so that the molecule has symmetry group D5h.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] In the gas phase, electron diffraction and computational studies show that the Cp rings are eclipsed.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] While ferrocene has no permanent dipole moment at room temperature, between 172.8 and 163.5 K (−148.6 and −165.4 °F; −100.3 and −109.6 °C) the molecule exhibits an "incommensurate modulation", breaking the D5 symmetry and acquiring an electric dipole.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] In solution, eclipsed D5h ferrocene was determined to dominate over the staggered D5d conformer, as suggested by both Fourier-transform infrared spectroscopy and DFT calculations.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The first reported syntheses of ferrocene were nearly simultaneous.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Pauson and Kealy synthesised ferrocene using iron(III) chloride and cyclopentadienyl magnesium bromide.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] A redox reaction produces iron(II) chloride.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The formation of fulvalene (the intended outcome), does not occur.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Another early synthesis of ferrocene was by Miller *et al.*, who treated metallic iron with gaseous cyclopentadiene at elevated temperature.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] An approach using iron pentacarbonyl was also reported.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Electrophiles typically substitute onto, rather than add to, the cyclopentadienyl ligands.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] For example, a common undergraduate experiment performs Friedel-Crafts acylation with acetic anhydride and a phosphoric acid catalyst.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Just as this reagent mixture converts benzene to acetophenone, it converts ferrocene to acetylferrocene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] In the presence of aluminium chloride, dimethylaminophosphorus dichloride (Me2NPCl2) and ferrocene react to give ferrocenyl dichlorophosphine, whereas treatment with dichlorophenylphosphine under similar conditions forms *P*,*P*-diferrocenyl-*P*-phenyl phosphine.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Vilsmeier-Haack formylation using *N*-methylformanilide and phosphorus oxychloride gives ferrocenecarboxaldehyde.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Unsubstituted ferrocene undergoes aromatic substitution more easily than benzene, because electrophiles can attack the metal ion before rearranging to the Wheland intermediate.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Thus ferrocene reacts with the weak electrophile Phosphorus pentasulfide (P4S10) to form a diferrocenyl-dithiadiphosphetane disulfide.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Mannich conditions suffice to iminylate ferrocene to N,N-Dimethylaminomethylferrocene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] For stronger electrophiles, the major reaction pathway is direct (*exo*) attack on the ring, without any metal participation.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Superacidic protonation does not complete aromatic substitution, but rather traps the unrearranged bent intermediate hydrido salt, [Cp2FeH]PF6.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Strongly-oxidizing electrophiles, such as halogens and nitric acid, neither rearrange to a Wheland intermediate nor coordinate to iron, instead generating ferrocenium salts (see § Redox chemistry).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] In accordance with cluster compound theory, ferrocene's rings behave as a single delocalized π system.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Electronic perturbations to one ring propagate to the other.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] For example, introduction of a deactivating aldehyde group on one ring inhibits formylation of the other ring as well.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene reacts with butyllithium to give 1,1′-dilithioferrocene, which is a versatile nucleophile.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] In combination with butyllithium, *tert*-butyllithium produces monolithioferrocene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Likewise ferrocene mercurates to give ferrocendiyl dimercuriacetate.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Further reaction gives the nitro, halo-, and borono derivatives.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene undergoes a one-electron oxidation at around 0.4 V versus a saturated calomel electrode (SCE), becoming **ferrocenium**.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Although the nomenclature is not internally consistent, ferrocenium is abbreviated **Fc+**.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] This reversible oxidation has been used as standard in electrochemistry as Fc+/Fc = 0.64 V versus the standard hydrogen electrode, however other values have been reported.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocenium tetrafluoroborate is a common reagent.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The remarkably reversible oxidation-reduction behaviour has been extensively used to control electron-transfer processes in electrochemical and photochemical systems.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Thus, decamethylferrocene is much more easily oxidised than ferrocene and can even be oxidised to the corresponding dication.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene is often used as an internal standard for calibrating redox potentials in non-aqueous electrochemistry.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Monosubstituted ferrocenes have the formula (C5H5)Fe(C5H4R).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] These derivatives are often referred to as **ferrocenyl** (abbreviated **Fc**) compounds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Examples include ferrocenyl aldehyde (FcCHO), ferrocenyl carboxylic acid (FcCO2H), and ferrocenyl methanol (FcCH2OH).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] When the substituent is chiral, then the entire molecule is chiral.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Disubstituted ferrocenes can exist as either 1,2-, 1,3- or 1,1′- isomers, none of which are interconvertible.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocenes that are asymmetrically disubstituted on one ring are chiral – for example [CpFe(EtC5H3Me)].
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] This planar chirality arises despite no single atom being a stereogenic centre.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Several approaches have been developed to asymmetrically 1,1′-functionalise the ferrocene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene and its numerous derivatives have no large-scale applications, but have many niche uses that exploit the unusual structure (ligand scaffolds, pharmaceutical candidates), robustness (anti-knock formulations, precursors to materials), and redox (reagents and redox standards).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Chiral ferrocenyl phosphines are employed as ligands for transition-metal catalyzed reactions.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Some of them have found industrial applications in the synthesis of pharmaceuticals and agrochemicals.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] For example, the diphosphine 1,1′-bis(diphenylphosphino)ferrocene (dppf) is a valued ligand for palladium-coupling reactions and Josiphos ligand is useful for hydrogenation catalysis.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] They are named after the technician who made the first one, Josi Puleo.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene and its derivatives are antiknock agents used in the fuel for petrol engines.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] They are safer than previously used tetraethyllead.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Petrol additive solutions containing ferrocene can be added to unleaded petrol to enable its use in vintage cars designed to run on leaded petrol.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The iron-containing deposits formed from ferrocene can form a conductive coating on spark plug surfaces.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene polyglycol copolymers, prepared by effecting a polycondensation reaction between a ferrocene derivative and a substituted dihydroxy alcohol, has promise as a component of rocket propellants.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] These copolymers provide rocket propellants with heat stability, serving as a propellant binder and controlling propellant burn rate.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene has been found to be effective at reducing smoke and sulfur trioxide produced when burning coal.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The addition by any practical means, impregnating the coal or adding ferrocene to the combustion chamber, can significantly reduce the amount of these undesirable byproducts, even with a small amount of the metal cyclopentadienyl compound.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene derivatives have been investigated as drugs, with one compound ferrocerone approved for use in the USSR in the 1970s as an iron supplement, though it is no longer marketed today.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Only one drug has entered clinical trials in recent years, Ferroquine (7-chloro-N-(2-((dimethylamino)methyl)ferrocenyl)quinolin-4-amine), an antimalarial, which has reached Phase IIb trials.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene-containing polymer-based drug delivery systems have been investigated.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The anticancer activity of ferrocene derivatives was first investigated in the late 1970s, when derivatives bearing amine or amide groups were tested against lymphocytic leukemia.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Some ferrocenium salts exhibit anticancer activity, but no compound has seen evaluation in the clinic.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene derivatives have strong inhibitory activity against human lung cancer cell line A549, colorectal cancer cell line HCT116, and breast cancer cell line MCF-7.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] An experimental drug was reported which is a ferrocenyl version of tamoxifen.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The idea is that the tamoxifen will bind to the estrogen binding sites, resulting in cytotoxicity.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocifens are exploited for cancer applications by a French biotech, Feroscan, founded by Pr.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene and related derivatives are used as powerful burn rate catalysts in ammonium perchlorate composite propellant.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] As a substituent on alkyl (or similar) compounds, ferrocene is one of the strongest σ-donating groups known.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene analogues can be prepared with variants of cyclopentadienyl.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] For example, bisindenyliron and bisfluorenyliron.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Carbon atoms can be replaced by heteroatoms as illustrated by Fe(η5-C5Me5)(η5-P5) and Fe(η5-C5H5)(η5-C4H4N) ("azaferrocene").
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Azaferrocene arises from decarbonylation of Fe(η5-C5H5)(CO)2(η1-pyrrole) in cyclohexane.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] This compound on boiling under reflux in benzene is converted to ferrocene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Iron arene complexes are possible, but bis(arene)s are difficult to stabilize.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The bis(benzene)iron(II) cation, isoelectronic with bis(benzene)chromium, is unstable against nucleophilic attack, and decomposes "instantaneously" in acetonitrile.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] It can be observed, however, in metastable nitromethane solution.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Because of the ease of substitution, many structurally unusual ferrocene derivatives have been prepared.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] For example, the penta(ferrocenyl)cyclopentadienyl ligand, features a cyclopentadienyl anion derivatized with five ferrocene substituents.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] In **hexaferrocenylbenzene**, C6[(η5-C5H4)Fe(η5-C5H5)]6, all six positions on a benzene molecule have ferrocenyl substituents (**R**).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] X-ray diffraction analysis of this compound confirms that the cyclopentadienyl ligands are not co-planar with the benzene core but have alternating dihedral angles of 30° and −80°.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Due to steric crowding the ferrocenyls are slightly bent with angles of 177° and have elongated C-Fe bonds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The quaternary cyclopentadienyl carbon atoms are also pyramidalized.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Also, the benzene core has a chair conformation with dihedral angles of 14° and displays bond length alternation between 1.411 and 1.427 Å, both indications of steric crowding of the substituents.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The yield is only 4%, which is further evidence consistent with substantial steric crowding around the arene core.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Ferrocene, a precursor to iron nanoparticles, can be used as a catalyst for the production of carbon nanotubes.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Vinylferrocene can be converted to (polyvinylferrocene, PVFc), a ferrocenyl version of polystyrene (the phenyl groups are replaced with ferrocenyl groups).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Another polyferrocene which can be formed is poly(2-(methacryloyloxy)ethyl ferrocenecarboxylate), PFcMA.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] Both PVFc and PFcMA have been tethered onto silica wafers and the wettability measured when the polymer chains are uncharged and when the ferrocene moieties are oxidised to produce positively charged groups.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] The contact angle with water on the PFcMA-coated wafers was 70° smaller following oxidation, while in the case of PVFc the decrease was 30°, and the switching of wettability is reversible.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/ferrocene] In the PFcMA case, the effect of lengthening the chains and hence introducing more ferrocene groups is significantly larger reductions in the contact angle upon oxidation.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Grignard compounds are popular reagents in organic synthesis for creating new carbon–carbon bonds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] The carbon-magnesium bond in Grignard reagent is a polar covalent bond.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] The carbon atom has negative excess charge and acts as a nucleophile.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Grignard reagents are rarely isolated as solids.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Instead, they are normally handled as solutions in solvents such as diethyl ether or tetrahydrofuran using air-free techniques.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Grignard reagents are complexes with the magnesium atom bonded to two ether ligands as well as the halide and organyl ligands.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] The discovery of the Grignard reaction in 1900 was recognized with the Nobel Prize awarded to Victor Grignard in 1912.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Traditionally Grignard reagents are prepared by treating an organic halide (normally organobromine) with magnesium metal.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Ethers are required to stabilize the organomagnesium compound.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Water and air, which rapidly destroy the reagent by protonolysis or oxidation, are excluded.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Although the reagents still need to be dry, ultrasound can allow Grignard reagents to form in wet solvents by activating the magnesium such that it consumes the water.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] As is common for reactions involving solids and solution, the formation of Grignard reagents is often subject to an induction period.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] During this stage, the passivating oxide on the magnesium is removed.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] After this induction period, the reactions can be highly exothermic.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] This exothermicity must be considered when a reaction is scaled-up from laboratory to production plant.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Most organohalides will work, but carbon-fluorine bonds are generally unreactive, except with specially activated magnesium (through Rieke metals).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Typically the reaction to form Grignard reagents involves the use of magnesium ribbon.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] All magnesium is coated with a passivating layer of magnesium oxide, which inhibits reactions with the organic halide.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Many methods have been developed to weaken this passivating layer, thereby exposing highly reactive magnesium to the organic halide.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Mechanical methods include crushing of the Mg pieces in situ, rapid stirring, and sonication.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Iodine, methyl iodide, and 1,2-dibromoethane are common activating agents.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] The use of 1,2-dibromoethane is advantageous as its action can be monitored by the observation of bubbles of ethylene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] The amount of Mg consumed by these activating agents is usually insignificant.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] When treated with small amounts of mercuric chloride, magnesium pieces become coated with an amalgam, enhancing its reactivity.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Activated magnesium, such as Rieke magnesium, circumvents this problem.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] The oxide layer can also be broken up using ultrasound, using a stirring rod to scratch the oxidized layer off, or by adding a few drops of iodine or 1,2-Diiodoethane.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Another option is to use sublimed magnesium or magnesium anthracene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] An alternative preparation of Grignard reagents involves transfer of Mg from a preformed Grignard reagent to an organic halide.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Other organomagnesium reagents are used as well.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] This method offers the advantage that the Mg transfer tolerates many functional groups.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] A further method to synthesize Grignard reagents involves reaction of Mg with an organozinc compound.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] This method has been used to make adamantane-based Grignard reagents, which are, due to C-C coupling side reactions, difficult to make by the conventional method from the alkyl halide and Mg.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Grignard reagents with chloride, bromide, and iodide are routine reagents.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] The corresponding fluorides RMgF were not synthesized until 1970.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] In 1920 Swarts reported the reduction of amyl fluoride to the corresponding hydrocarbon with activated magnesium, although no intermediates were identified.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Alkylmagnesium fluorides were first prepared by Ashby and co-workers in 1970, using magnesium, catalytic iodine, alkyl fluoride in refluxing tetrahydrofuran or 1,2-dimethoxyethane.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Because Grignard reagents are so sensitive to moisture and oxygen, many methods have been developed to test the quality of a batch.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Typical tests involve titrations with weighable, anhydrous protic reagents, e.g. menthol in the presence of a color-indicator.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] The interaction of the Grignard reagent with phenanthroline or 2,2'-biquinoline causes a color change.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Grignard reagents react with a variety of carbonyl derivatives.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Such reactions usually involve an aqueous acidic workup, though this step is rarely shown in reaction schemes.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] The most common application of Grignard reagents is the alkylation of aldehydes and ketones, i.e.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Note that the acetal functional group (a protected carbonyl) does not react.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Compounds with labile protons are unsuitable electrophiles, because Grignard reagents are strong bases, and protonative quenching occurs much faster than addition.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Grignard reagents are basic and react with alcohols, phenols, etc. to give alkoxides (ROMgBr).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] 1,3-Diketones and related substrates are also acidic enough that the Grignard reagent RMgX functions merely as a base, liberating the alkane RH to give a magnesium enolate.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Most Grignard reactions are conducted in ethereal solvents, especially diethyl ether and THF.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] This reaction exploits the Schlenk equilibrium, driving it toward the right.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Grignard reagents do *not* typically react with organic halides, in contrast with their high reactivity with other main group halides.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] In the presence of metal catalysts, however, Grignard reagents participate in C-C coupling reactions.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] For example, nonylmagnesium bromide reacts with methyl *p*-chlorobenzoate to give *p*-nonylbenzoic acid, in the presence of Tris(acetylacetonato)iron(III) (Fe(acac)3), after workup with NaOH to hydrolyze the ester, shown as follows.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Without the Fe(acac)3, the Grignard reagent would attack the ester group over the aryl halide.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] For the coupling of aryl halides with aryl Grignard reagents, nickel chloride in tetrahydrofuran (THF) is also a good catalyst.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Additionally, an effective catalyst for the couplings of alkyl halides is the Gilman catalyst lithium tetrachlorocuprate (Li2CuCl4), prepared by mixing lithium chloride (LiCl) and copper(II) chloride (CuCl2) in THF.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] The Kumada-Corriu coupling gives access to (substituted) styrenes.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Treatment of a Grignard reagent with oxygen gives the magnesium organoperoxide.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Hydrolysis of this material yields hydroperoxides or alcohol.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] These reactions involve radical intermediates.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] The simple oxidation of Grignard reagents to give alcohols is of little practical importance as yields are generally poor.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Oxidations of Grignard reagents with oxygen (O2) in presence of an alkene can give an ethylene-extended alcohol.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] This modification requires aryl or vinyl Grignard reagents.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] The Grignard and the alkene do not react, demonstrating that oxygen is essential for the coupling.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] One drawback to this procedure is the requirement of at least two equivalents of Grignard although this can partly be circumvented by the use of a dual Grignard system with a cheap reducing Grignard such as *n*-butylmagnesium bromide.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] In the Boord olefin synthesis, the addition of magnesium to certain β-haloethers results in an elimination reaction to the alkene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] This reaction can limit the utility of Grignard reactions.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/grignard-reagent] Allyl Grignard reagents exhibit high reactivity and special selectivity compared to alkyl ones.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] A **metallocene** is a compound typically consisting of two cyclopentadienyl anions (C 5H− 5, abbreviated Cp) bound to a metal center (M).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] They have the general formula (C5R5)2M]+ (R = H, alkyl typically).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Closely related to the metallocenes are the metallocene derivatives, e.g. titanocene dichloride or vanadocene dichloride.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Certain metallocenes and their derivatives exhibit catalytic properties, although metallocenes are rarely used industrially.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Cationic group 4 metallocene derivatives related to [Cp2ZrCH3]+ catalyze olefin polymerization.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Metallocenes are a subset of a broader class of compounds called sandwich compounds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] In the structure shown at right, the two pentagons are the cyclopentadienyl anions with circles inside them indicating they are aromatically stabilized.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Here they are shown in a staggered conformation.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] The first metallocene was ferrocene, discovered simultaneously in 1951 by Kealy and Pauson, and Miller et al.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] The structure of "C10H10Fe" was determined by Geoffrey Wilkinson et al. and by Ernst Otto Fischer et al.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] These two were awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1973 for their work on sandwich compounds, including the structural determination of ferrocene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] They determined that the carbon atoms of the cyclopentadienyl (Cp) ligand contributed equally to the bonding and that bonding occurred due to the metal d-orbitals and the π-electrons in the p-orbitals of the Cp ligands.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] This complex is now known as ferrocene, and the group of transition metal dicyclopentadienyl compounds is known as metallocenes.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Metallocenes have the general formula [(*η*5-C5H5)2M].
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Fischer et al. first prepared the ferrocene derivatives involving Co and Ni.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Often derived from substituted derivatives of cyclopentadienide, metallocenes of many elements have been prepared.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] The general name metallocene is derived from ferrocene, (C5H5)2Fe or Cp2Fe, systematically named bis(*η*5-cyclopentadienyl)iron(II).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] According to the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) definition, a metallocene contains a transition metal and two cyclopentadienyl ligands coordinated in a sandwich structure, i.e., the two cyclopentadienyl anions are on parallel planes with equal bond lengths and strengths.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Using the nomenclature of "hapticity", the equivalent bonding of all 5 carbon atoms of a cyclopentadienyl ring is denoted as *η*5, pronounced "pentahapto".
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] In metallocene names, the prefix before the *-ocene* ending indicates what metallic element is between the Cp groups.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] For example, in ferrocene, iron(II), ferrous iron is present.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Although not sanctioned by IUPAC, uranocene, with two cyclooctatetraene rings sandwiching a uranium atom is sometimes classified as a metallocene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Some "metallocene" complexes of actinides have been reported where there are three cyclopentadienyl ligands for a monometallic complex, all three of them bound η5.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Titanocene dichloride (Cp2TiCl2) is yet another common violation of the IUPAC guidelines.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Sodium cyclopentadienide (NaCp) is the preferred reagent for these types of reactions.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] It is most easily obtained by the reaction of molten sodium and dicyclopentadiene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Traditionally, the starting point is the cracking of dicyclopentadiene, the dimer of cyclopentadiene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Cyclopentadiene is deprotonated by strong bases or alkali metals.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] NaCp acts as a reducing agent and a ligand in this reaction.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] This technique provides using metal atoms in the gas phase rather than the solid metal.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] The highly reactive atoms or molecules are generated at a high temperature under vacuum and brought together with chosen reactants on a cold surface.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] A variety of reagents have been developed that transfer Cp to metals.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Once popular was thallium cyclopentadienide.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] It reacts with metal halides to give thallium chloride, which is poorly soluble, and the cyclopentadienyl complex.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Trialkyltin derivatives of Cp− have also been used.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Metallocenes generally have high thermal stability.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Ferrocene can be sublimed in air at over 100 °C with no decomposition; metallocenes are generally purified in the laboratory by vacuum sublimation.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Industrially, sublimation is not practical so metallocenes are isolated by crystallization or produced as part of a hydrocarbon solution.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] For Group IV metallocenes, donor solvents like ether or THF are distinctly undesirable for polyolefin catalysis.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Charge-neutral metallocenes are soluble in common organic solvents.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Alkyl substitution on the metallocene increases the solubility in hydrocarbon solvents.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] A structural trend for the series MCp2 involves the variation of the M-C bonds, which elongate as the valence electron count deviates from 18.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] In metallocenes of the type (C5R5)2M, the cyclopentadienyl rings rotate with very low barriers.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Single crystal X-ray diffraction studies reveal both eclipsed or staggered rotamers.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] For non-substituted metallocenes the energy difference between the staggered and eclipsed conformations is only a few kJ/mol.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Crystals of ferrocene and osmocene exhibit eclipsed conformations at low temperatures, whereas in the related bis(pentamethylcyclopentadienyl) complexes the rings usually crystallize in a staggered conformation, apparently to minimize steric hindrance between the methyl groups.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Infrared and Raman spectroscopies have proved to be important in the analysis of cyclic polyenyl metal sandwich species, with particular use in elucidating covalent or ionic M–ring bonds and distinguishing between central and coordinated rings.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) is the most applied tool in the study of metal sandwich compounds and organometallic species, giving information on nuclear structures in solution, as liquids, gases, and in the solid state.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] 1H NMR chemical shifts for paramagnetic organotransition-metal compounds is usually observed between 25 and 40 ppm, but this range is much more narrow for diamagnetic metallocene complexes, with chemical shifts usually observed between 3 and 7 ppm.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Mass spectrometry of metallocene complexes has been very well studied and the effect of the metal on the fragmentation of the organic moiety has received considerable attention and the identification of metal-containing fragments is often facilitated by the isotope distribution of the metal.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] The three major fragments observed in mass spectrometry are the molecular ion peak, [C10H10M]+, and fragment ions, [C5H5M]+ and M+.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] After the discovery of ferrocene, the synthesis and characterization of derivatives of metallocene and other sandwich compounds attracted researchers’ interests.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Metallocenophanes feature linking of the cyclopentadienyl or polyarenyl rings by the introduction of one or more heteroannular bridges.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Some of these compounds undergo thermal ring-opening polymerizations to give soluble high molecular weight polymers with transition metals in the polymer backbone.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Ansa-metallocenes are derivatives of metallocenes with an intramolecular bridge between the two cyclopentadienyl rings.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Triple-decker complexes are composed of three Cp anions and two metal cations in alternating order.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] The first triple-decker sandwich complex, [Ni2Cp3]+, was reported in 1972.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Many examples have been reported subsequently, often with boron-containing rings.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] The most famous example is ferrocenium, [Fe(C5H5)2]+, the blue iron(III) complex derived from oxidation of orange iron(II) ferrocene.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] The lithocene anion, [Li(C5H5)2]–, is the best-documented example of a metallocene anion; otherwise such ions are little known.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Many derivatives of early metal metallocenes are active catalysts for olefin polymerization.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Unlike traditional and still dominant heterogeneous Ziegler–Natta catalysts, metallocene catalysts are homogeneous.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Early metal metallocene derivatives, e.g.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Tebbe's reagent, Petasis reagent, and Schwartz's reagent are useful in specialized organic synthetic operations.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] The ferrocene/ferrocenium biosensor has been discussed for determining the levels of glucose in a sample electrochemically through a series of connected redox cycles.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/metallocene] Metallocene dihalides [Cp2MX2] (M = Ti, Mo, Nb) exhibit anti-tumor properties, although none have proceeded far in clinical trials.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Organometallic compounds are distinguished by the prefix "organo-" (e.g., organopalladium compounds), and include all compounds which contain a bond between a metal atom and a carbon atom of an organyl group.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] In addition to the traditional metals (alkali metals, alkali earth metals, transition metals, and post transition metals), lanthanides, actinides, semimetals, and the elements boron, silicon, arsenic, and selenium are considered to form organometallic compounds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Examples of organometallic compounds include Gilman reagents, which contain lithium and copper, and Grignard reagents, which contain magnesium.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Boron-containing organometallic compounds are often the result of hydroboration and carboboration reactions.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Tetracarbonyl nickel and ferrocene are examples of organometallic compounds containing transition metals.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] A naturally occurring organometallic complex is methylcobalamin (a form of Vitamin B12), which contains a cobalt-methyl bond.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] This complex, along with other biologically relevant complexes are often discussed within the subfield of bioorganometallic chemistry.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Many complexes feature coordination bonds between a metal and organic ligands.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Complexes where the organic ligands bind the metal through a heteroatom such as oxygen or nitrogen are considered coordination compounds (e.g., heme A and Fe(acac)3).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] However, if any of the ligands form a direct metal-carbon (M-C) bond, then the complex is considered to be organometallic.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Although the IUPAC has not formally defined the term, some chemists use the term "metalorganic" to describe any coordination compound containing an organic ligand regardless of the presence of a direct M-C bond.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] The status of compounds in which the canonical anion has a negative charge that is shared between (delocalized) a carbon atom and an atom more electronegative than carbon (e.g. enolates) may vary with the nature of the anionic moiety, the metal ion, and possibly the medium.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] In the absence of direct structural evidence for a carbon–metal bond, such compounds are not considered to be organometallic.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] For instance, lithium enolates often contain only Li-O bonds and are not organometallic, while zinc enolates (Reformatsky reagents) contain both Zn-O and Zn-C bonds, and are organometallic in nature.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] The metal-carbon bond in organometallic compounds is generally highly covalent.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] For highly electropositive elements, such as lithium and sodium, the carbon ligand exhibits carbanionic character, but free carbon-based anions are extremely rare, an example being cyanide.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Most organometallic compounds are solids at room temperature, however some are liquids such as methylcyclopentadienyl manganese tricarbonyl, or even volatile liquids such as nickel tetracarbonyl.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Many organometallic compounds are air sensitive.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Some organometallic compounds such as triethylaluminium are pyrophoric and will ignite on contact with air.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] As in other areas of chemistry, electron counting is useful for organizing organometallic chemistry.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] The 18-electron rule is helpful in predicting the stabilities of organometallic complexes, for example metal carbonyls and metal hydrides.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] The 18e rule has two representative electron counting models, ionic and neutral (also known as covalent) ligand models, respectively.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] The hapticity of a metal-ligand complex, can influence the electron count.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Hapticity (η, lowercase Greek eta), describes the number of contiguous ligands coordinated to a metal.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] For example, ferrocene, [(η5-C5H5)2Fe], has two cyclopentadienyl ligands giving a hapticity of 5, where all five carbon atoms of the C5H5 ligand bond equally and contribute one electron to the iron center.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Ligands that bind non-contiguous atoms are denoted the Greek letter kappa, κ.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] The covalent bond classification method identifies three classes of ligands, X, L, and Z; which are based on the electron donating interactions of the ligand.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Many organometallic compounds do not follow the 18e rule.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] The metal atoms in organometallic compounds are frequently described by their d electron count and oxidation state.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] These concepts can be used to help predict their reactivity and preferred geometry.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Chemical bonding and reactivity in organometallic compounds is often discussed from the perspective of the isolobal principle.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] A wide variety of physical techniques are used to determine the structure, composition, and properties of organometallic compounds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] X-ray diffraction is a particularly important technique that can locate the positions of atoms within a solid compound, providing a detailed description of its structure.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Other techniques like infrared spectroscopy and nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy are also frequently used to obtain information on the structure and bonding of organometallic compounds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Ultraviolet-visible spectroscopy is a common technique used to obtain information on the electronic structure of organometallic compounds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] It is also used monitor the progress of organometallic reactions, as well as determine their kinetics.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] The dynamics of organometallic compounds can be studied using dynamic NMR spectroscopy.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Other notable techniques include X-ray absorption spectroscopy, electron paramagnetic resonance spectroscopy, and elemental analysis.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Due to their high reactivity towards oxygen and moisture, organometallic compounds often must be handled using air-free techniques.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Air-free handling of organometallic compounds typically requires the use of laboratory apparatuses such as a glovebox or Schlenk line.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Recognition of organometallic chemistry as a distinct subfield culminated in the Nobel Prizes to Ernst Fischer and Geoffrey Wilkinson for work on metallocenes.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Schrock shared the Nobel Prize for metal-catalyzed olefin metathesis.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Organometallic compounds find wide use in commercial reactions, both as homogenous catalysts and as stoichiometric reagents.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] For instance, organolithium, organomagnesium, and organoaluminium compounds, examples of which are highly basic and highly reducing, are useful stoichiometrically but also catalyze many polymerization reactions.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Almost all processes involving carbon monoxide rely on catalysts, notable examples being described as carbonylations.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] The production of acetic acid from methanol and carbon monoxide is catalyzed via metal carbonyl complexes in the Monsanto process and Cativa process.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Most synthetic aldehydes are produced via hydroformylation.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] The bulk of the synthetic alcohols, at least those larger than ethanol, are produced by hydrogenation of hydroformylation-derived aldehydes.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Similarly, the Wacker process is used in the oxidation of ethylene to acetaldehyde.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Almost all industrial processes involving alkene-derived polymers rely on organometallic catalysts.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] The world's polyethylene and polypropylene are produced via both heterogeneously via Ziegler–Natta catalysis and homogeneously, e.g., via constrained geometry catalysts.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Most processes involving hydrogen rely on metal-based catalysts.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Whereas bulk hydrogenations (e.g., margarine production) rely on heterogeneous catalysts, for the production of fine chemicals such hydrogenations rely on soluble (homogenous) organometallic complexes or involve organometallic intermediates.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Organometallic complexes allow these hydrogenations to be effected asymmetrically.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Many semiconductors are produced from trimethylgallium, trimethylindium, trimethylaluminium, and trimethylantimony.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] These volatile compounds are decomposed along with ammonia, arsine, phosphine and related hydrides on a heated substrate via metalorganic vapor phase epitaxy (MOVPE) process in the production of light-emitting diodes (LEDs).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] The synthesis of many organic molecules are facilitated by organometallic complexes.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Sigma-bond metathesis is a synthetic method for forming new carbon-carbon sigma bonds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Sigma-bond metathesis is typically used with early transition-metal complexes that are in their highest oxidation state.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Using transition-metals that are in their highest oxidation state prevents other reactions from occurring, such as oxidative addition.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] In addition to sigma-bond metathesis, olefin metathesis is used to synthesize various carbon-carbon pi bonds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Neither sigma-bond metathesis or olefin metathesis change the oxidation state of the metal.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Many other methods are used to form new carbon-carbon bonds, including beta-hydride elimination and insertion reactions.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Organometallic complexes are commonly used in catalysis.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Major industrial processes include hydrogenation, hydrosilylation, hydrocyanation, olefin metathesis, alkene polymerization, alkene oligomerization, hydrocarboxylation, methanol carbonylation, and hydroformylation.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] The catalytically active organometallic species are often generated in situ starting from commercially available metal salts.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Organometallic intermediates are also invoked in many heterogeneous catalysis processes, analogous to those listed above.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Additionally, organometallic intermediates are assumed for Fischer–Tropsch process.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Organometallic complexes are commonly used in fine chemical synthesis as well, especially in cross-coupling reactions that form carbon-carbon bonds, e.g.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Suzuki-Miyaura coupling, Buchwald-Hartwig amination for producing aryl amines from aryl halides, and Sonogashira coupling, etc.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Organometallic species are also involved in photoredox catalysis, although not on a commercial scale.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Natural and contaminant organometallic compounds are found in the environment.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Some that are remnants of human use, such as organolead and organomercury compounds, are toxicity hazards.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Tetraethyllead was prepared for use as a gasoline additive but has fallen into disuse because of lead's toxicity.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Its replacements are other organometallic compounds, such as ferrocene and methylcyclopentadienyl manganese tricarbonyl (MMT).
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] The organoarsenic compound roxarsone is a controversial animal feed additive.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] In 2006, approximately one million kilograms of it were produced in the U.S alone.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/organometallic-chemistry] Organotin compounds were once widely used in anti-fouling paints but have since been banned due to environmental concerns.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] For transition metals, oxidative reaction results in the decrease in the d*n* to a configuration with fewer electrons, often 2e fewer.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Oxidative addition is favored for metals that are (i) basic and/or (ii) easily oxidized.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] In classical organometallic chemistry, the formal oxidation state of the metal and the electron count of the complex both increase by two.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] One-electron changes are also possible and in fact some oxidative addition reactions proceed via series of 1e changes.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Although oxidative additions can occur with the insertion of a metal into many different substrates, oxidative additions are most commonly seen with H–H, H–X, and C–X bonds because these substrates are most relevant to commercial applications.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Oxidative addition requires that the metal complex have a vacant coordination site.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] For this reason, oxidative additions are common for four- and five-coordinate complexes.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Reductive elimination is the reverse of oxidative addition.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Reductive elimination is favored when the newly formed X–Y bond is strong.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] For reductive elimination to occur the two groups (X and Y) should be mutually adjacent on the metal's coordination sphere.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Reductive elimination is the key product-releasing step of several reactions that form C–H and C–C bonds.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Oxidative additions proceed by diverse pathways that depend on the metal center and the substrates.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Oxidative additions of nonpolar substrates such as hydrogen and hydrocarbons appear to proceed via concerted pathways.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Such substrates lack π-bonds, consequently a three-centered σ complex is invoked, followed by intramolecular ligand bond cleavage of the ligand (probably by donation of electron pair into the sigma* orbital of the inter ligand bond) to form the oxidized complex.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] The resulting ligands will be mutually *cis*, although subsequent isomerization may occur.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] This mechanism applies to the addition of homonuclear diatomic molecules such as H2.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Many C–H activation reactions also follow a concerted mechanism through the formation of an M–(C–H) agostic complex.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] A representative example is the reaction of hydrogen with Vaska's complex, *trans*-IrCl(CO)[P(C6H5)3]2.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] In this transformation, iridium changes its formal oxidation state from +1 to +3.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] The product is formally bound to three anions: one chloride and two hydride ligands.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] As shown below, the initial metal complex has 16 valence electrons and a coordination number of four whereas the product is a six-coordinate 18 electron complex.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Formation of a trigonal bipyramidal dihydrogen intermediate is followed by cleavage of the H–H bond, due to electron back donation into the H–H σ*-orbital, i.e. a sigma complex.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] This system is also in chemical equilibrium, with the reverse reaction proceeding by the elimination of hydrogen gas with simultaneous reduction of the metal center.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] The electron back donation into the H–H σ*-orbital to cleave the H–H bond causes electron-rich metals to favor this reaction.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] The concerted mechanism produces a *cis* dihydride, while the stereochemistry of the other oxidative addition pathways do not usually produce *cis* adducts.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Some oxidative additions proceed analogously to the well known bimolecular nucleophilic substitution reactions in organic chemistry.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Nucleophilic attack by the metal center at the less electronegative atom in the substrate leads to cleavage of the R–X bond, to form an [M–R]+ species.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] This step is followed by rapid coordination of the anion to the cationic metal center.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] This mechanism is often assumed in the addition of polar and electrophilic substrates, such as alkyl halides and halogens.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] The ionic mechanism of oxidative addition is similar to the SN2 type in that it involves the stepwise addition of two distinct ligand fragments.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] The key difference being that ionic mechanisms involve substrates which are dissociated in solution prior to any interactions with the metal center.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] An example of ionic oxidative addition is the addition of hydrogen chloride.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Water and amines may oxidatively add to late transition metals via a protonative mechanism with a cyclic transition state involving several water/amine molecules.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] In addition to undergoing SN2-type reactions, alkyl halides and similar substrates can add to a metal center via a radical mechanism, although some details remain controversial.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Reactions which are generally accepted to proceed by a radical mechanism are known however.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] One example was proposed by Lednor and co-workers.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Oxidative addition and reductive elimination are invoked in many catalytic processes in homogeneous catalysis, e.g., hydrogenations, hydroformylations, hydrosilylations, etc.
[src:organometallic-chemistry/oxidative-addition] Cross-coupling reactions like the Suzuki coupling, Negishi coupling, and the Sonogashira coupling also proceed by oxidative addition.
